{"name": "pg-asynq", "metadata": {"name": "pg-asynq", "version": "0.1.0", "classifiers": ["License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.11", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.12", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.13", "Topic :: Database"], "home_page": "https://github.com/amithkk/pg-asynq", "license": "MIT", "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": ["orjson"], "summary": "Barebones async-powered message queue on python with psycopg (v3)", "upload_time": 1733683871}, "documentation": ["# PG-AsynQ\n\nPG-AsynQ is a Python library that provides an asynchronous transaction/message queue based on PostgreSQL. \nIt is inspired by [pq](https://pypi.org/project/pq/), but is built for use in asynchronous contexts such as FastAPI, \nand uses psycopg 3.x for database access.\n\nNon blocking queuing is implemented with a combination of `LISTEN/NOTIFY` and `SKIP LOCKED`. This means that this \nlibrary is safe to use across multiple containers/processes without duplicated processing of messages.\n\n# How to use\n\n1. Ensure you create the tables in [migrations](./migrations) using your preferred migration tool\n2. See the [examples](./examples) for how to use the library\n\n# Features\n\n- [x] Create and consume queues dynamically at runtime\n- [x] Consume queue from any number of consumers\n- [x] Retain messages until a consumer connects\n- [x] In-order processing of messages\n- [ ] Message retention policies (delete older than x)\n"], "modules": [{"name": "pg_asynq", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [], "classes": [], "exports": [{"name": "pg_asynq.AsynqJSONMessage", "xref": {"fqname": "helpers.AsynQMessage.AsynqJSONMessage", "project": null}}, {"name": "pg_asynq.AsynqManager", "xref": {"fqname": "AsynqManager.AsynqManager", "project": null}}, {"name": "pg_asynq.AsynqMessage", "xref": {"fqname": "helpers.AsynQMessage.AsynqMessage", "project": null}}]}, {"name": "pg_asynq.helpers.Asy